text.paragraph:
      See Table 7 and  Table 8 for a listing of potentially significant drug interactions [see 

                              Drug  Interactions  (7.1

                            ,


                                 7.2
                              ) 
                           ].

Serious hypersensitivity reactions including, anaphylaxis and anaphylactic shock, during or soon after infusion of fosaprepitant have occurred. Symptoms including flushing, erythema, dyspnea, hypotension and syncope have been reported [

                              see Adverse Reactions (6.2

                           )].

                           Monitor patients during and after infusion. If hypersensitivity reactions occur, discontinue the infusion and administer appropriate medical therapy. Do not reinitiate fosaprepitant in patients who experience these symptoms  with previous use [ 

                              see contraindications (4

                           )].

Coadministration  of   fosaprepitant with  warfarin,  a  CYP2C9  substrate,  may  result  in  a  clinically  significant  decrease  in  the  International  Normalized  Ratio  (INR)  of  prothrombin  time  [see 


                              Clinical  Pharmacology (12.3)

                           ]  Monitor  the  INR  in  patients  on  chronic  warfarin  therapy  in  the  2-week  period,  particularly  at  7  to 10  days,  following  initiation  of  fosaprepitant with  each  chemotherapy  cycle  [see  
                                 Drug  Interactions  (7.1)


                           ].

tr.td:
Increased  exposure  to  midazolam  or  other  benzodiazepines  metabolized  via  CYP3A4  (alprazolam, triazolam) may increase the risk of adverse reactions [
                                          see Clinical Pharmacology  (12.3)
                                       ].

Increased dexamethasone exposure [
                                          see Clinical Pharmacology  (12.3
                                       )].

Reduce  the  dose  of  oral  dexamethasone  by  approximately  50%  [
                                          see  Dosage  and  Administration  (2.1
                                       )].

Increased methylprednisolone exposure [
                                          see Clinical Pharmacology  (12.3)
                                       ].

Increased  exposure  of  the  chemotherapeutic  agent  may  increase  the  risk  of  adverse  reactions  [
                                          see  Clinical Pharmacology  (12.3)
                                       ].

  No change in the exposure of the 5-HT3 antagonist [
                                          see Clinical Pharmacology  (12.3
                                       )].
